\n**WHAT'S GOING ON**\nOn December 11, 2025, the President signed an executive order trying to wipe out state laws that regulate Artificial Intelligence [1]. The federal government is basically saying they do not want fifty different local rules for AI; they want one national framework, and they want that framework to be as hands-off as possible [1]. To force the states into line, Washington is setting up a special task force of lawyers to sue them [5]. They are also threatening to cut off federal funding meant for broadband internet infrastructure if states refuse to repeal their local AI safety laws [2]. \n\n**WHY THIS IS A BIG DEAL**\nStates like Colorado and California have been busy passing laws that force AI developers to test their systems for hidden biases and be transparent about their training data [6]. The administration argues this patchwork of state rules is a giant hurdle that slows down American innovation in a competitive global race [1, 5]. But if you exist outside the tech industry, you should pay attention. The federal government is specifically targeting laws that try to fix algorithmic discrimination [7]. They are trying to declare that forcing an AI to mitigate bias is actually a \"deceptive trade practice\" because it alters the machine's \"truthful output\" [7]. They are literally arguing that correcting an AI's learned societal bias makes the machine less faithful to its underlying data [7].\n\n**UNCOMFORTABLE TRUTH**\nHere is the tricky part: an executive order by itself does not actually have the magic power to instantly erase state laws [4]. Only the courts or an act of Congress can actually strike down a law, meaning we are stepping into a period of deep, unpredictable uncertainty [3, 4]. The real friction here is that this maneuver creates a massive, messy legal gray area [3]. Tech companies are squirming because they are caught in the crossfire; they still have to obey the state laws today and face penalties if they do not, all while the federal government drags these states into a legal battle that could take years to reach the Supreme Court [3, 4]. \n\n**SO WHAT**\nThe federal government declared war on state AI regulations, but until judges actually strike them down, companies still have to follow the local laws tomorrow [3, 4].",
