\n**WHAT'S GOING ON**\nBlock, the financial tech company that makes Square and Cash App, just fired about 4,000 people [2]. That is nearly 40% of their entire staff, taking them from over 10,000 employees down to fewer than 6,000 [1, 2]. The CEO, Jack Dorsey, didn't hide behind the usual corporate excuses about \"macroeconomic headwinds.\" He came right out and posted on X that they are eliminating these jobs because artificial intelligence tools are cheaper and efficient enough to replace them [1, 2].\n\n**WHY THIS IS A BIG DEAL**\nYou know how people have been saying AI is just a \"copilot,\" a little helper to make you work faster? Well, if a tool makes a worker twice as fast, a company doesn't always double its output\u2014sometimes it just fires half the workers. This is a watershed moment because it is one of the first times a major, publicly traded tech company has explicitly drawn a straight line between adopting AI and firing thousands of humans [1]. Anyone outside the tech industry should be paying attention to this. If a massive financial infrastructure can suddenly slice away half of its human brainpower and keep running on algorithms, the fundamental equation of human labor has changed. It means the friction of running a giant company just dropped, and the need for human cogs just evaporated.\n\n**UNCOMFORTABLE TRUTH**\nHere is the thing nobody really wants to admit: the machine doesn't have to be perfect to take your job; it just has to be \"good enough\" and vastly cheaper than you. We like to think that our desk jobs require some special human spark, but the reality is a lot of so-called knowledge work is just routine data shuffling. We don't know for sure exactly which 4,000 jobs were cut\u2014whether it was customer service, coding, or middle management\u2014but the friction here is obvious. The corporate world is waking up to the fact that human employees are expensive, slow, and suddenly optional for a lot of daily tasks. \"AI adoption\" isn't just about empowering workers; it is an active mechanism for worker elimination [1]. \n\n**SO WHAT**\nThe era of humans competing only against other humans for desk jobs is over; starting today, you are competing against a server rack.",
