\n**WHAT'S GOING ON**\nAnthropic, Google, and OpenAI just caught their competitors red-handed stealing their homework [1, 2]. Chinese AI labs, including DeepSeek and Moonshot, set up tens of thousands of fake user accounts to relentlessly ask questions to models like Claude and ChatGPT [1-3]. But they weren't just asking questions to get answers; they were systematically extracting the step-by-step logic the models use to solve problems [2, 3]. It's a process called \"distillation.\" Instead of spending years and massive resources figuring out how to make a machine think, these rivals just recorded the smart machines thinking out loud and used that data to train their own models [1, 2]. \n\n**WHY THIS IS A BIG DEAL**\nTo build a top-tier AI, you need an ocean of high-quality data and computing power that costs billions of dollars. But what happens if you can just bypass all of that? Anthropic alone tracked over 16 million automated exchanges coming from about 24,000 dummy accounts [3]. This means the bottleneck in the global AI race isn't just about who has the biggest supercomputer anymore. It's about intellectual property theft happening right out in the open through standard user interfaces [2]. If anyone can just siphon the \"smarts\" out of a frontier model for pennies on the dollar, the fundamental economics of the entire tech industry collapse [2]. We are watching a new kind of espionage where the prize isn't a secret blueprint in a vault, but the invisible reasoning patterns of a computer program [2].\n\n**UNCOMFORTABLE TRUTH**\nThe uncomfortable truth is that it is practically impossible to distinguish a real user asking a hard question from a bot scraping data to train a rival AI. These companies built open, accessible platforms\u2014APIs\u2014so developers could invent cool things. Now, those exact same open doors are the vulnerability [2]. If companies lock down their systems too hard to stop the theft, they ruin the product for legitimate users. If they don't lock them down, they are essentially subsidizing their fiercest geopolitical competitors for free. Nobody actually knows how to permanently plug these API loopholes without breaking the very openness that made the AI boom possible in the first place [2]. \n\n**SO WHAT**\nThe era of open AI development is slamming shut as tech giants are forced to build massive walls to protect their machines' thoughts from being cloned [2].",
